<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-06-07T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-06-07T16:00:00-05:00" n="885" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d885">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conference 184.01602/57a:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Commission to Negotiate
                                    Peace</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Naval Station at
                                    Constantinople</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-06-07T22:00:00+01:00"><hi rend="italic">June 7,
                                        1919—10 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>384. For Berry, Ekaterinodar.</p>
                        <p>Current reports here state 200 Russians repatriated from France mutinied
                            at Novorossiisk and were exterminated. Can you cable <pb facs="0875" n="763" xml:id="pg_763"/> facts? Has any word of the Allied note to
                                <persName corresp="#p_KAAV1">Kolchak</persName><note n="14" xml:id="d885fn14"><hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_367">p. 367</ref>.</note> been received at Ekaterinodar and if so
                            what is the attitude of the Volunteer Army and the Kouban
                            Government?</p>
                        <closer><hi rend="smallcaps">Am</hi>[<hi rend="smallcaps">erican</hi>] <hi rend="smallcaps">Mission</hi></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>